{"title_page": "Olmec hieroglyphs", "text_new": "The [[Olmecs]] were the earliest known major [[Mesoamerica]]n [[civilization]]. The Olmecs flourished during [[Mesoamerica]]'s [[Mesoamerican chronology|formative period]] (1500 [[Before the Common Era|BCE]] to 400 BCE) in the tropical lowlands of the modern-day Mexican states of [[Veracruz]] and [[Tabasco]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Diehl|first=Richard A.|url=https://archive.org/details/olmecsamericasfi0000dieh/page/9|title=The Olmecs : America's First Civilization|publisher=Thames and Hudson|year=2004|isbn=0-500-28503-9|location=London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/olmecsamericasfi0000dieh/page/9 9\u201325]|authorlink=Richard Diehl}}</ref> The subsequent [[Epi-Olmec culture]] (300 BCE to 250 CE), was a successor culture to the Olmec and featured a full-fledged writing system, the [[Isthmian script|Isthmian (or Epi-Olmec) script]].\n\nThe existence of a [[writing system]] in Middle and Late Olmec periods has been a matter of long-standing debate. Evidence includes the appearance of individual (potential) glyphs as well as the singleton [[Cascajal Block]] that bears a potential text.\n\n==Periodization==\n=== Cascajal block (approx. 900 BCE) ===\n{{Main|Cascajal Block}}\n[[File:Cascajal-text.svg|right|thumb|The 62 glyphs of the [[Cascajal block]]]]\nIn September 2006, a report published in Science magazine announced the discovery of the Cascajal block, a writing-tablet-sized block of serpentine with 62 characters unlike any yet seen in Mesoamerica. This block was discovered by locals in the Olmec heartland and was dated by the archaeologists to approximately 900 BCE based on other debris. If the authenticity and date can be verified, this will prove to be the earliest writing yet found in Mesoamerica. The symbols on the Cascajal block are unlike those of any other writing system in Mesoamerica, such as in [[Mayan languages]] or [[Isthmian script|Isthmian]], another extinct Mesoamerican script. The Cascajal block is also unusual because the symbols apparently run in horizontal rows and \"there is no strong evidence of overall organization. The sequences appear to be conceived as independent units of information\".<ref>{{cite journal|author=Rodr\u00edguez Mart\u00ednez, Ma. del Carmen|author2=Ponciano Ort\u00edz Ceballos|author3=Michael D. Coe|author3-link=Michael D. Coe|author4=Richard A. Diehl|author5=Stephen D. Houston|author5-link=Stephen D. Houston|author6=Karl A. Taube|author6-link=Karl A. Taube|author7=Alfredo Delgado Calder\u00f3n|date=2006-09-16|title=Oldest Writing in the New World|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/full/313/5793/1610|journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|location=Washington, DC|publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]|volume=313|issue=5793|pages=1610\u20131614|doi=10.1126/science.1131492|oclc=200349481|pmid=16973873|bibcode=2006Sci...313.1610R}}</ref> The 28 unique Cascajal block characters bear no obvious resemblance to later glyphs. If indeed, it has been a script, \"[the Cascajal block script] apparently left no descendants, with no certain link to [[Isthmian script|Isthmian]] or other Formative [period] writing.\" (Skidmore 2007,p.5)<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mesoweb.com/reports/cascajal.html|title=The Cascajal Block: The Earliest Precolumbian Writing|author=Skidmore, Joel|year=2006|website=Mesoweb Reports & News|publisher=Mesoweb|format=[[PDF]]|accessdate=2007-06-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Potential glyphs (650 \u2013 400 BCE) ===\nIt was long thought that many of the glyphs present on Olmec monumental sculpture, such as those on the so-called \"Ambassador Monument\" ([[La Venta]] Monument 13, tentatively dated to 650 \u2013 450 BCE <ref>{{Cite book|last=Rice|first=Prudence M.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=2b_DoSfVKnUC&pg=PA96&lpg=PA96&dq=la+venta+ambassador+13#v=onepage|title=Maya Calendar Origins: Monuments, Mythistory, and the Materialization of Time|date=2009-02-17|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=978-0-292-77449-0|location=|pages=96|language=en}}</ref>), represented an early Olmec script. Other potential glyphs have been found on portable objects such as celts,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mayadecipherment.com/2015/01/26/the-royal-headband-a-pan-mesoamerican-hieroglyph-for-ruler/|title=The Royal Headband: A Pan-Mesoamerican Hieroglyph|last=Stuart|first=David|date=2015-01-26|website=Maya Decipherment|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> sherds, etc. However, several glyphs clearly continue symbols previously established in ''iconography'' rather than writing,<ref>F. Kent Reilly, III (1996), [http://www.mesoweb.com/pari/publications/RT10/32_LazyS.html The Lazy-S: A Formative Period Iconographic Loan to Maya Hieroglyphic Writing], In Martha J. Macri and Jan McHargue (eds.), ''Eighth Palenque Round Table, 1993''\u00a0.<br /></ref> so that their use for recording spoken language can only be ascertained if multiple potential glyphs are combined. \n\n[[File:Proposed Olmec glyphs (San Andres).svg|150px|thumb|San Andr\u00e9s [[Glyph (archaeology)|glyph]]s. The top set of glyphs have been interpreted as \"3 Ajaw\". The bottom two glyphs were found incised into semi-precious [[greenstone (archaeology)|greenstone]] artifacts.|alt=|left]]\n\n[[File:San_Andres_Cylinder_Seal_print_1.svg|alt=|thumb|375x375px|A rollout of the San Andr\u00e9s cylinder seal, showing the bird possibly \"speaking\" the name \"3 Ajaw\"]]\n\nIn 2002, one such a glyph group was confirmed for two possible glyphs at [[San Andres (Mesoamerican site)|San Andres]]:<ref>https://science.sciencemag.org/content/298/5600/1984/tab-figures-data</ref> Excavations conducted in 1997 and 1998 produced three artifacts that many archaeologists contend demonstrate that the Olmec civilization used a true writing system. These artifacts, dated roughly to 650 BCE (the middle of the Olmec concentration at La Venta and San Andres), were found in a refuse dump, the remains from a festival or feast. \u201cThe fact that the artifacts with glyphs were found in the context of feasting refuse suggest that writing among the Olmec was sacred and was closely tied to ritual activities.\u201d <ref>{{cite journal|last=Pohl|first=Mary|year=2005|title=Olmec Civilization at San Andr\u00e9s, Tabasco, M\u00e9xico|url=|journal=Foundation for the Advancement of Mesoamerican Studies, Inc. (FAMSI)|volume=|pages=10|via=}}</ref>  The most important find was a fist-sized ceramic cylinder seal, likely used to print cloth. When rolled out, the seal shows two [[Speech scroll|speech scrolls]] emanating from a bird, followed directly by a number of design elements enframing what has been interpreted as logograms for \u201cking (sideways U shape),\u201d \"3 (three dots, according to the Mesoamerican bar and dots numbering system),\u201d and \u201cAjaw (from the sacred 260-day calendar)\", a designation used for both a calendar date and, in keeping with Mesoamerican custom, the name of an Olmec ruler. In addition to the ceramic cylinder seal, two fingernail-sized fragments from a greenstone plaque have been recovered, each containing an incised glyph. Both these glyphs have been linked to well-documented glyphs in other Mesoamerican writing systems, including the Isthmian (Epi-Olmec) and Maya scripts.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Pohl, Mary|authorlink=|author2=Kevin O. Pope|author3=Christopher von Nagy|year=2002|title=Olmec Origins of Mesoamerican Writing|url=|journal=Science|volume=298|issue=5600|pages=1984\u20131985|doi=10.1126/science.1078474|pmid=12471256|bibcode=2002Sci...298.1984P|accessdate=|quote=}}</ref> \n\nWell-known archaeologist and writer Michael D. Coe interprets the San Andres glyphs as \"an early kind of writing\" <ref name=\":1\">{{aut|Bower, Bruce}} \"Script Delivery: New World writing takes disputed turn\" in ''Science News'', Vol. 162, No. 23, December 7, 2002, p. 355.</ref> while Richard A. Diehl, who excavated at the Olmec site of San Lorenzo Tenochtitlan with Coe, finds that this discovery \"establishes the existence of Olmec writing and calendrics by 650 B.C.E\" <ref>{{cite book|author=Diehl, Richard|url=https://archive.org/details/olmecsamericasfi0000dieh|title=The Olmecs: America's First Civilization|publisher=[[Thames & Hudson]]|year=2004|isbn=978-0-500-02119-4|series=Ancient peoples and places series|location=London|pages=96|oclc=56746987|authorlink=Richard Diehl|url-access=registration}}</ref> On the other hand, Mayanist epigrapher David Stuart stated that it would be hard to discern evidence of a writing system in a handful of symbols.<ref name=\":1\" /> The question was complicated in 2006 by the discovery of the [[Cascajal Block]]. The 28 unique Cascajal block characters bear no obvious resemblance to the San Andres glyphs and are, indeed, unlike those of any other Mesoamerican writing system.<ref name=\":0\" />  Questions concerning the interpretation of the San Andr\u00e9s glyphs (and the Cascajal block) will need to await further research.\n\nA cylinder seal from [[Tlatilco]], dated to a time frame of Olmec occupation, appears to carry a non-pictographic, linear script.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kelley|first=David H.|date=July 1966|title=A Cylinder Seal from Tlatilco|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S0002731600095226/type/journal_article|journal=American Antiquity|language=en|volume=31|issue=5Part1|pages=744\u2013746|doi=10.2307/2694503|jstor=2694503|issn=0002-7316}}</ref> A cylinder seal from [[Chiapa de Corzo (Mesoamerican site)|Chiapa de Corzo]], Mexico, also appears to be an example of an unknown Mesoamerican script.{{Clarify|reason=This is drawn from a Kelley (1966). Is it possible that this \"seal\" is one of the artifacts (sherd, stele, pendant) from this site that is now considerded to be Early Isthmian writing (cf. https://www.researchgate.net/publication/318672076_Isthmian_Script_at_Chiapa_de_Corzo) ? Not according to the illustrations, but if it is not found to be a forgery, it is surprising that the seal is not mentioned by Macri (2017).|date=April 2020}} Both have been discussed as potential evidence for Olmec writing as they appeared during a time of [[Olmec influences on Mesoamerican cultures|Olmec influence]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kelley|first1=David H.|date=1966|title=A Cylinder Seal from Tlatilco|journal=American Antiquity|volume=31|issue=5|pages=744\u201346|doi=10.2307/2694503|jstor=2694503}}</ref>\n\n[[File:La_Mojarra_Estela_1_(Escritura_superior).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|Detail showing glyphs from 2nd century CE [[La Mojarra Stela 1]] currently located at the Museum of Anthropology of Xalapa, Veracruz, Mexico. The left column gives a Long Count date of 8.5.16.9.9, or 162 CE. The other columns are glyphs from the [[Epi-Olmec script]].]]\n\n\n=== Epi-Olmec or Isthmian script (300 BCE onwards) ===\n[[File:Stela2,Chiapa_de_Corzo.JPG|right|thumb|Chiapa de Corzo Stela 2, showing the date of 7.16.3.2.13, or December 36 BCE, the earliest [[Mesoamerican Long Count calendar]] date yet found.]]\n{{Main|Epi-Olmec script}}\nA small number of Epi-Olmec artifacts found in the [[Isthmus of Tehuantepec]] show examples of an early Mesoamerican writing system which \u201cmay itself descend from an Olmec hieroglyphic system, but too little of the Olmec script has been recovered to confirm or disprove a connection\u201d (Justeson and Kaufman 1993:1703).<ref>Justeson, John S. and Terrence Kaufman (1993), A Decipherment of Epi-Olmec Hieroglyphic Writing. Science, 19 March 1993, pp. 1703\u20131711.</ref>\n\nThe longest of these texts are on [[La Mojarra Stela 1]] and the [[Tuxtla Statuette]]. The writing system used is very close (and possibly ancestral) to the [[Maya script]], using affixal glyphs and [[Mesoamerican Long Count calendar|Long Count]] dates, but is read only in one column at a time as is the Zapotec script. An Epi-Olmec stela from Chiapa de Corzo is the oldest monument of the Americas inscribed with its own date: the [[Maya calendar#Long Count|Long Count]] dates it to 36 BCE. A sherd from Chiapa de Corzo dated to 300 BCE was held to be the oldest instance of that [[Mesoamerican writing systems|writing system]] yet discovered,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albany.edu/anthro/maldp/EOTEXTS.pdf|title=Epi-Olmec Hieroglyphic Writing and Texts|author=Justeson, John S.|author2=Terrence Kaufman|year=2001|accessdate=2010-01-02}} p. 2.</ref> but more recently, it has been been suggested that early Isthmian writing at Chiapa de Corzo even pre-dates the Epi-Olmec culture.<ref>Macri, Martha. (2017). [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/318672076_Isthmian_Script_at_Chiapa_de_Corzo Isthmian Script at Chiapa de Corzo]. Glyph Dweller.</ref>\n\nIn a 1997 paper, John Justeson and Terrence Kaufman put forward a decipherment of Epi-Olmec. The following year, however, their interpretation was disputed by Stephen Houston and [[Michael D. Coe]], who unsuccessfully applied Justeson and Kaufman's decipherment system against epi-Olmec script from the back of a hitherto unknown mask. The matter remains under dispute.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Mesoamerican writing systems]]\n[[Category:Proto-writing]]\n[[Category:Olmec]]\n[[Category:Formative period in the Americas]]\n[[Category:Inscriptions in undeciphered writing systems]]\n[[Category:Mesoamerican inscriptions]]\n", "text_old": "The [[Olmecs]] were the earliest known major [[Mesoamerica]]n [[civilization]]. The Olmecs flourished during [[Mesoamerica]]'s [[Mesoamerican chronology|formative period]] (1500 [[Before the Common Era|BCE]] to 400 BCE) in the tropical lowlands of the modern-day Mexican states of [[Veracruz]] and [[Tabasco]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Diehl|first=Richard A.|url=https://archive.org/details/olmecsamericasfi0000dieh/page/9|title=The Olmecs : America's First Civilization|publisher=Thames and Hudson|year=2004|isbn=0-500-28503-9|location=London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/olmecsamericasfi0000dieh/page/9 9\u201325]|authorlink=Richard Diehl}}</ref> The subsequent [[Epi-Olmec culture]] (300 BCE to 250 CE), was a successor culture to the Olmec and featured a full-fledged writing system, the [[Isthmian script|Isthmian (or Epi-Olmec) script]].\n\nThe existence of a [[writing system]] in Middle and Late Olmec periods has been a matter of long-standing debate. Evidence includes the appearance of individual (potential) glyphs as well as the singleton [[Cascajal Block]] that bears a potential text.\n\n==Periodization==\n=== Cascajal block (approx. 900 BCE) ===\n{{Main|Cascajal Block}}\n[[File:Cascajal-text.svg|right|thumb|The 62 glyphs of the [[Cascajal block]]]]\nIn September 2006, a report published in Science magazine announced the discovery of the Cascajal block, a writing-tablet-sized block of serpentine with 62 characters unlike any yet seen in Mesoamerica. This block was discovered by locals in the Olmec heartland and was dated by the archaeologists to approximately 900 BCE based on other debris. If the authenticity and date can be verified, this will prove to be the earliest writing yet found in Mesoamerica. The symbols on the Cascajal block are unlike those of any other writing system in Mesoamerica, such as in [[Mayan languages]] or [[Isthmian script|Isthmian]], another extinct Mesoamerican script. The Cascajal block is also unusual because the symbols apparently run in horizontal rows and \"there is no strong evidence of overall organization. The sequences appear to be conceived as independent units of information\".<ref>{{cite journal|author=Rodr\u00edguez Mart\u00ednez, Ma. del Carmen|author2=Ponciano Ort\u00edz Ceballos|author3=Michael D. Coe|author3-link=Michael D. Coe|author4=Richard A. Diehl|author5=Stephen D. Houston|author5-link=Stephen D. Houston|author6=Karl A. Taube|author6-link=Karl A. Taube|author7=Alfredo Delgado Calder\u00f3n|date=2006-09-16|title=Oldest Writing in the New World|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/full/313/5793/1610|journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|location=Washington, DC|publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]|volume=313|issue=5793|pages=1610\u20131614|doi=10.1126/science.1131492|oclc=200349481|pmid=16973873|bibcode=2006Sci...313.1610R}}</ref> The 28 unique Cascajal block characters bear no obvious resemblance to later glyphs. If indeed, it has been a script, \"[the Cascajal block script] apparently left no descendants, with no certain link to [[Isthmian script|Isthmian]] or other Formative [period] writing.\" (Skidmore 2007,p.5)<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mesoweb.com/reports/cascajal.html|title=The Cascajal Block: The Earliest Precolumbian Writing|author=Skidmore, Joel|year=2006|website=Mesoweb Reports & News|publisher=Mesoweb|format=[[PDF]]|accessdate=2007-06-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Potential glyphs (650 - 400 BCE) ===\nIt was long thought that many of the glyphs present on Olmec monumental sculpture, such as those on the so-called \"Ambassador Monument\" ([[La Venta]] Monument 13, tentatively dated to 650 - 450 BCE <ref>{{Cite book|last=Rice|first=Prudence M.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=2b_DoSfVKnUC&pg=PA96&lpg=PA96&dq=la+venta+ambassador+13#v=onepage|title=Maya Calendar Origins: Monuments, Mythistory, and the Materialization of Time|date=2009-02-17|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=978-0-292-77449-0|location=|pages=96|language=en}}</ref>), represented an early Olmec script. Other potential glyphs have been found on portable objects such as celts,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mayadecipherment.com/2015/01/26/the-royal-headband-a-pan-mesoamerican-hieroglyph-for-ruler/|title=The Royal Headband: A Pan-Mesoamerican Hieroglyph|last=Stuart|first=David|date=2015-01-26|website=Maya Decipherment|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> sherds, etc. However, several glyphs clearly continue symbols previously established in ''iconography'' rather than writing,<ref>F. Kent Reilly, III (1996), [http://www.mesoweb.com/pari/publications/RT10/32_LazyS.html The Lazy-S: A Formative Period Iconographic Loan to Maya Hieroglyphic Writing], In Martha J. Macri and Jan McHargue (eds.), ''Eighth Palenque Round Table, 1993''\u00a0.<br /></ref> so that their use for recording spoken language can only be ascertained if multiple potential glyphs are combined. \n\n[[File:Proposed Olmec glyphs (San Andres).svg|150px|thumb|San Andr\u00e9s [[Glyph (archaeology)|glyph]]s. The top set of glyphs have been interpreted as \"3 Ajaw\". The bottom two glyphs were found incised into semi-precious [[greenstone (archaeology)|greenstone]] artifacts.|alt=|left]]\n\n[[File:San_Andres_Cylinder_Seal_print_1.svg|alt=|thumb|375x375px|A rollout of the San Andr\u00e9s cylinder seal, showing the bird possibly \"speaking\" the name \"3 Ajaw\"]]\n\nIn 2002, one such a glyph group was confirmed for two possible glyphs at [[San Andres (Mesoamerican site)|San Andres]]:<ref>https://science.sciencemag.org/content/298/5600/1984/tab-figures-data</ref> Excavations conducted in 1997 and 1998 produced three artifacts that many archaeologists contend demonstrate that the Olmec civilization used a true writing system. These artifacts, dated roughly to 650 BCE (the middle of the Olmec concentration at La Venta and San Andres), were found in a refuse dump, the remains from a festival or feast. \u201cThe fact that the artifacts with glyphs were found in the context of feasting refuse suggest that writing among the Olmec was sacred and was closely tied to ritual activities.\u201d <ref>{{cite journal|last=Pohl|first=Mary|year=2005|title=Olmec Civilization at San Andr\u00e9s, Tabasco, M\u00e9xico|url=|journal=Foundation for the Advancement of Mesoamerican Studies, Inc. (FAMSI)|volume=|pages=10|via=}}</ref>  The most important find was a fist-sized ceramic cylinder seal, likely used to print cloth. When rolled out, the seal shows two [[Speech scroll|speech scrolls]] emanating from a bird, followed directly by a number of design elements enframing what has been interpreted as logograms for \u201cking (sideways U shape),\u