vious resemblance to the San Andres glyphs and are, indeed, unlike those of any other Mesoamerican writing system.<ref name=\":0\" />  Questions concerning the interpretation of the San Andr\u00e9s glyphs (and the Cascajal block) will need to await further research.\n\nA cylinder seal from [[Tlatilco]], dated to a time frame of Olmec occupation, appears to carry a non-pictographic, linear script.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kelley|first=David H.|date=July 1966|title=A Cylinder Seal from Tlatilco|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S0002731600095226/type/journal_article|journal=American Antiquity|language=en|volume=31|issue=5Part1|pages=744\u2013746|doi=10.2307/2694503|jstor=2694503|issn=0002-7316}}</ref> A cylinder seal from [[Chiapa de Corzo (Mesoamerican site)|Chiapa de Corzo]], Mexico, also appears to be an example of an unknown Mesoamerican script.{{Clarify|reason=This is drawn from a Kelley (1966). Is it possible that this \"seal\" is one of the artifacts (sherd, stele, pendant) from this site that is now considerded to be Early Isthmian writing (cf. https://www.researchgate.net/publication/318672076_Isthmian_Script_at_Chiapa_de_Corzo) ? Not according to the illustrations, but if it is not found to be a forgery, it is surprising that the seal is not mentioned by Macri (2017).|date=April 2020}} Both have been discussed as potential evidence for Olmec writing as they appeared during a time of [[Olmec influences on Mesoamerican cultures|Olmec influence]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kelley|first1=David H.|date=1966|title=A Cylinder Seal from Tlatilco|journal=American Antiquity|volume=31|issue=5|pages=744\u201346|doi=10.2307/2694503|jstor=2694503}}</ref>\n\n[[File:La_Mojarra_Estela_1_(Escritura_superior).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|Detail showing glyphs from 2nd century CE [[La Mojarra Stela 1]] currently located at the Museum of Anthropology of Xalapa, Veracruz, Mexico. The left column gives a Long Count date of 8.5.16.9.9, or 162 CE. The other columns are glyphs from the [[Epi-Olmec script]].]]\n\n\n=== Epi-Olmec or Isthmian script (300 BCE onwards) ===\n[[File:Stela2,Chiapa_de_Corzo.JPG|right|thumb|Chiapa de Corzo Stela 2, showing the date of 7.16.3.2.13, or December 36 BCE, the earliest [[Mesoamerican Long Count calendar]] date yet found.]]\n{{Main|Epi-Olmec script}}\nA small number of Epi-Olmec artifacts found in the [[Isthmus of Tehuantepec]] show examples of an early Mesoamerican writing system which \u201cmay itself descend from an Olmec hieroglyphic system, but too little of the Olmec script has been recovered to confirm or disprove a connection\u201d (Justeson and Kaufman 1993:1703).<ref>Justeson, John S. and Terrence Kaufman (1993), A Decipherment of Epi-Olmec Hieroglyphic Writing. Science, 19 March 1993, pp. 1703-1711.</ref>\n\nThe longest of these texts are on [[La Mojarra Stela 1]] and the [[Tuxtla Statuette]]. The writing system used is very close (and possibly ancestral) to the [[Maya script]], using affixal glyphs and [[Mesoamerican Long Count calendar|Long Count]] dates, but is read only in one column at a time as is the Zapotec script. An Epi-Olmec stela from Chiapa de Corzo is the oldest monument of the Americas inscribed with its own date: the [[Maya calendar#Long Count|Long Count]] dates it to 36 BCE. A sherd from Chiapa de Corzo dated to 300 BCE was held to be the oldest instance of that [[Mesoamerican writing systems|writing system]] yet discovered,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albany.edu/anthro/maldp/EOTEXTS.pdf|title=Epi-Olmec Hieroglyphic Writing and Texts|author=Justeson, John S.|author2=Terrence Kaufman|year=2001|accessdate=2010-01-02}} p. 2.</ref> but more recently, it has been been suggested that early Isthmian writing at Chiapa de Corzo even pre-dates the Epi-Olmec culture.<ref>Macri, Martha. (2017). [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/318672076_Isthmian_Script_at_Chiapa_de_Corzo Isthmian Script at Chiapa de Corzo]. Glyph Dweller.</ref>\n\nIn a 1997 paper, John Justeson and Terrence Kaufman put forward a decipherment of Epi-Olmec. The following year, however, their interpretation was disputed by Stephen Houston and [[Michael D. Coe]], who unsuccessfully applied Justeson and Kaufman's decipherment system against epi-Olmec script from the back of a hitherto unknown mask. The matter remains under dispute.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Mesoamerican writing systems]]\n[[Category:Proto-writing]]\n[[Category:Olmec]]\n[[Category:Formative period in the Americas]]\n[[Category:Inscriptions in undeciphered writing systems]]\n[[Category:Mesoamerican inscriptions]]\n", "name_user": "Diannaa", "label": "safe", "comment": "Attribution: text was moved here fromSan Andr\u00e9s (Mesoamerican site)on April 24, 2020. Please see the history of that page for full attribution.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olmec_hieroglyphs"}
